WEBVTT

1
00:00:00.620 --> 00:00:03.100
You can go home. Mike.
I'll finish closing up.

2
00:00:03.190 --> 00:00:04.760
Fortunately.
there's not much to do.

3
00:00:04.840 --> 00:00:06.556
since there were
barely any customers tonight.

4
00:00:06.580 --> 00:00:07.826
Sure. things
have slowed down

5
00:00:07.850 --> 00:00:09.460
a little
since the restaurant opened.

6
00:00:09.590 --> 00:00:11.460
And maybe they did
get some bad press

7
00:00:11.630 --> 00:00:14.640
from briefly becoming the Hudson
Valley's top Mafia hangout.

8
00:00:14.810 --> 00:00:16.550
But on the bright side...

9
00:00:18.070 --> 00:00:19.550
Oh. no. Pete can't
find a bright side.

10
00:00:19.730 --> 00:00:20.860
Hmm. this is bad.

11
00:00:20.990 --> 00:00:21.820
I don't get it.

12
00:00:21.990 --> 00:00:23.780
I'm serving great food.

13
00:00:23.910 --> 00:00:25.576
Meanwhile. Connor's place
is packed every night.

14
00:00:25.600 --> 00:00:28.430
They just did a write-up on
him in New York Magazine.

15
00:00:28.560 --> 00:00:31.090
Connor is this guy Jay hates
from culinary school.

16
00:00:31.220 --> 00:00:32.700
I bet he hired a publicist.

17
00:00:32.830 --> 00:00:34.660
What a douche.
Jay.

18
00:00:34.790 --> 00:00:35.660
you're a great chef.

19
00:00:35.790 --> 00:00:36.986
You just need to focus on you.

20
00:00:37.010 --> 00:00:38.310
As much as I hate to admit it.

21
00:00:38.440 --> 00:00:40.230
I agree with Samantha.

22
00:00:40.310 --> 00:00:42.930
The truth is.
my own life is a tragic tale

23
00:00:43.100 --> 00:00:45.320
about how an obsession
with a nemesis

24
00:00:45.450 --> 00:00:47.410
can derail
one's own promising career.

25
00:00:47.500 --> 00:00:50.500
I'm of course referring
to my infamous rivalry

26
00:00:50.670 --> 00:00:52.150
with Alexander Hamilton.

27
00:00:52.280 --> 00:00:53.590
Can I be honest. Isaac?

28
00:00:53.720 --> 00:00:54.840
I've never really understood

29
00:00:54.890 --> 00:00:56.330
what Hamilton
actually did to you.

30
00:00:56.460 --> 00:00:58.200
Weren't you just kind
of jealous of him?

31
00:00:58.330 --> 00:01:01.070
I've never shared this with you
because I was embarrassed.

32
00:01:01.200 --> 00:01:03.690
but that man ruined my chance

33
00:01:03.820 --> 00:01:06.170
to become someone
history remembers.

34
00:01:06.250 --> 00:01:08.080
'Tis a painful story to tell.

35
00:01:08.210 --> 00:01:10.650
But since it might help Jay.

36
00:01:10.780 --> 00:01:11.780
I'm willing to share it.

37
00:01:11.820 --> 00:01:12.960
Ooh. Dinner and a show.

38
00:01:13.040 --> 00:01:13.960
I like it.

39
00:01:14.040 --> 00:01:15.310
Buckle up.

40
00:01:15.440 --> 00:01:18.310
For tonight.
I shall tell you the tale

41
00:01:18.440 --> 00:01:22.230
of why I hate
Alexander Hamilton.

42
00:01:27.270 --> 00:01:29.840
The year is 1776.

43
00:01:29.970 --> 00:01:31.890
It is?
No. in the story.

44
00:01:32.060 --> 00:01:32.840
Oh.

45
00:01:33.020 --> 00:01:34.630
Our tale begins

46
00:01:34.760 --> 00:01:36.240
at a men's haberdashery.

47
00:01:36.370 --> 00:01:37.940
where I'd gone
to pick up a ruffle.

48
00:01:38.070 --> 00:01:40.640
an ornamental
but obligatory garment I needed

49
00:01:40.770 --> 00:01:43.900
for an important event
I was to attend that evening.

50
00:01:43.990 --> 00:01:45.706
Earlier in the week.
I had received an invitation

51
00:01:45.730 --> 00:01:48.510
from my mentor. John Jay.
to attend a dinner party

52
00:01:48.640 --> 00:01:50.380
at his Manhattan estate.

53
00:01:50.510 --> 00:01:54.000
But this was to be
no regular soiree.

54
00:01:55.080 --> 00:01:57.040
Scuse me.
I'll be with you shortly.

55
00:01:57.170 --> 00:01:58.830
This infernal wait.

56
00:01:58.960 --> 00:02:00.570
Give me service
or give me death.

57
00:02:01.700 --> 00:02:03.750
Oh. my God.

58
00:02:03.880 --> 00:02:05.570
Beatrice. look.

59
00:02:05.700 --> 00:02:07.010
It's Alexander Hamilton.

60
00:02:07.180 --> 00:02:08.506
We met at James
Madison's Easter party

61
00:02:08.530 --> 00:02:11.880
and had the most thrilling
exchange of ideas.

62
00:02:11.970 --> 00:02:13.190
Alexander. hello!

63
00:02:13.320 --> 00:02:15.280
Yeah.
I've-I've already been helped.

64
00:02:15.410 --> 00:02:17.110
Um...
Oh. no. no. no.
no. it's me.

65
00:02:17.190 --> 00:02:19.500
It's me. Isaac
Higgintoot.

66
00:02:19.590 --> 00:02:22.240
We met at James
Madison's Easter party.

67
00:02:22.330 --> 00:02:24.940
Right. Of course!

68
00:02:25.110 --> 00:02:27.730
You were the talk of the event.

69
00:02:27.810 --> 00:02:29.420
Oh. Mm.
Oh. Really?

70
00:02:29.550 --> 00:02:31.770
Oh.
Yes! Yes. you ate
that rotten pork pie

71
00:02:31.900 --> 00:02:33.120
and yakked in his carriage.

72
00:02:33.250 --> 00:02:35.120
He couldn't get
the scent out.

73
00:02:35.300 --> 00:02:36.950
It was a total write-off.

74
00:02:37.040 --> 00:02:40.430
Well. um. I will see
you at dinner tonight?

75
00:02:40.560 --> 00:02:43.310
Oh. Yeah. I-I don't think so.

76
00:02:43.440 --> 00:02:46.000
No. I'm-I'm going
to John Jay's house

77
00:02:46.140 --> 00:02:48.220
to discuss
a-a very important matter.

78
00:02:48.360 --> 00:02:50.180
Yes. I will be there. too.
Really?

79
00:02:50.310 --> 00:02:52.010
Yeah.
Oh. I...

80
00:02:52.140 --> 00:02:55.140
I kind of assumed
it was an exclusive event.

81
00:02:55.320 --> 00:02:56.750
It is an exclusive event.

82
00:02:56.930 --> 00:02:58.760
Huh.

83
00:02:58.890 --> 00:03:01.930
You're sure you're not thinking
about Albert Jay's party?

84
00:03:02.020 --> 00:03:04.550
I heard he's hosting
a... chili dump.

85
00:03:04.680 --> 00:03:06.020
Maybe... Is that... is that

86
00:03:06.160 --> 00:03:07.940
the party. maybe.
you're attending?
No.

87
00:03:08.110 --> 00:03:10.070
John Jay's.
To discuss

88
00:03:10.250 --> 00:03:11.530
the Declaration of Independence.

89
00:03:11.600 --> 00:03:13.510
Hmm. Well!

90
00:03:13.640 --> 00:03:15.160
Excellent! Ha!

91
00:03:15.250 --> 00:03:17.690
Well. you shall be
the voice of the common man.

92
00:03:17.820 --> 00:03:19.040
I'll see you there.

93
00:03:22.390 --> 00:03:24.610
Now. how can I help you?

94
00:03:24.740 --> 00:03:27.050
Yes. Isaac Higgintoot.
picking up my shirt ruffle.

95
00:03:27.180 --> 00:03:28.610
Unfortunately. we're all out.

96
00:03:28.740 --> 00:03:30.830
What? I reserved
mine two weeks ago.

97
00:03:30.960 --> 00:03:32.620
Well. it's not here.

98
00:03:32.750 --> 00:03:34.510
It's possible
that someone else picked it up.

99
00:03:34.580 --> 00:03:36.100
But it was under my name.

100
00:03:36.190 --> 00:03:38.010
I-Is there one at another store?

101
00:03:38.100 --> 00:03:40.490
I doubt it. It's
sort of peak ruffle season.

102
00:03:40.670 --> 00:03:42.736
Now. I could order one in.
It would take at least a week.

103
00:03:42.760 --> 00:03:45.190
But I'm going to John
Jay's house tonight.

104
00:03:45.330 --> 00:03:47.630
I heard that was an exclusive...
event.

105
00:03:47.760 --> 00:03:49.420
It is.

106
00:03:49.590 --> 00:03:51.070
Tune in next week

107
00:03:51.240 --> 00:03:53.160
for an ice-cold elimination
on...

108
00:03:53.290 --> 00:03:55.380
It's Getting Hot in Here.

109
00:03:56.420 --> 00:03:59.210
Cannot believe Victoria P.
Sleep with Austin.

110
00:03:59.300 --> 00:04:01.470
then send him home same night.

111
00:04:01.650 --> 00:04:03.430
Victoria P. is
going to hell.

112
00:04:06.170 --> 00:04:08.260
I'm back.

113
00:04:08.440 --> 00:04:09.350
Oh. my God!
Oy gevalt.

114
00:04:09.440 --> 00:04:10.570
Not again.

115
00:04:10.650 --> 00:04:12.050
Elias. what are you doing here?

116
00:04:12.220 --> 00:04:13.480
Come now. Henrietta.

117
00:04:13.610 --> 00:04:15.270
that's no way
to greet your husband.

118
00:04:15.440 --> 00:04:16.490
Greet you?

119
00:04:16.660 --> 00:04:17.880
Last time you visited.

120
00:04:18.010 --> 00:04:19.840
you tried to drag Peter to hell.

121
00:04:19.970 --> 00:04:20.840
Never mind all that.

122
00:04:20.970 --> 00:04:22.580
I come to you today

123
00:04:22.670 --> 00:04:24.150
with an opportunity!

124
00:04:24.280 --> 00:04:27.060
We not interested
in anything you have to say.

125
00:04:27.240 --> 00:04:28.460
Now. now. hear me out.

126
00:04:28.590 --> 00:04:30.370
You see.
my boss was very impressed

127
00:04:30.460 --> 00:04:32.280
that I returned to hell
voluntarily.

128
00:04:32.370 --> 00:04:34.396
There's not a lot of that.
what with all the flaying

129
00:04:34.420 --> 00:04:36.380
and the burning
and the bad Wi-Fi.

130
00:04:36.460 --> 00:04:38.510
So now I am

131
00:04:38.680 --> 00:04:40.030
on the management track.

132
00:04:40.120 --> 00:04:43.430
And I am one soul shy
of a big promotion.

133
00:04:43.510 --> 00:04:46.860
Oh. and you expect
one of us to volunteer

134
00:04:47.000 --> 00:04:48.690
to give you our soul?
I do.

135
00:04:48.820 --> 00:04:52.300
If you accept my offer
and commit your soul to hell.

136
00:04:52.440 --> 00:04:54.520
you will join me
on the management track.

137
00:04:54.660 --> 00:04:58.350
Instead of having
your toenails pried off daily.

138
00:04:58.490 --> 00:05:00.050
well. you could be doing
the prying.

139
00:05:00.180 --> 00:05:01.880
Or supervising the prying.

140
00:05:01.970 --> 00:05:04.060
You wouldn't even have
to return with me now.

141
00:05:04.140 --> 00:05:06.620
We could work out a time.
even years from now.

142
00:05:06.710 --> 00:05:08.360
that your cushy sentence
could begin.

143
00:05:08.500 --> 00:05:11.540
But refuse my deal

144
00:05:11.630 --> 00:05:15.070
and risk an eternity
of pain and suffering.

145
00:05:15.240 --> 00:05:16.590
Elias. it's a no from us.

146
00:05:16.720 --> 00:05:18.680
So why don't you go try
to peddle your nonsense

147
00:05:18.810 --> 00:05:20.160
on some other ghosts.

148
00:05:20.330 --> 00:05:22.290
Oh. I specifically came
to talk to you four.

149
00:05:22.420 --> 00:05:24.990
You see. we've kind of had
our eyes on you.

150
00:05:25.160 --> 00:05:26.470
Well. I don't like that.

151
00:05:26.560 --> 00:05:27.820
I'm going to be fine.

152
00:05:27.950 --> 00:05:29.390
I'll have you know.
when I was alive.

153
00:05:29.430 --> 00:05:30.870
I gave a lot
of money to charity.

154
00:05:30.950 --> 00:05:32.870
Charity was
a dancer at Scores.

155
00:05:33.000 --> 00:05:34.000
One last thing...

156
00:05:34.090 --> 00:05:36.350
this offer expires at midnight.

157
00:05:36.440 --> 00:05:39.220
So. the only question is...

158
00:05:40.530 --> 00:05:42.490
are you willing
to roll the dice?

159
00:05:43.880 --> 00:05:45.230
Jay. pay attention.

160
00:05:45.360 --> 00:05:47.400
I can't hear or see him.

161
00:05:47.530 --> 00:05:49.450
Anyway. as I was saying.
that evening.

162
00:05:49.540 --> 00:05:51.020
I journeyed to John Jay's house.

163
00:05:51.150 --> 00:05:53.240
eager for the opportunity
that lay before me.

164
00:05:53.370 --> 00:05:54.800
but terrified

165
00:05:54.930 --> 00:05:57.540
by how my ruffle-less chest
would be received.

166
00:05:57.670 --> 00:05:59.280
I get it.
Neckwear was very important

167
00:05:59.370 --> 00:06:00.940
to us Pinecone Troopers.

168
00:06:01.070 --> 00:06:03.266
Although. given a second chance.
I would've gone with Kevlar

169
00:06:03.290 --> 00:06:05.120
and not your standard
cotton neckerchief.

170
00:06:05.250 --> 00:06:07.470
So. what happened when you got
to John Jay's house?

171
00:06:07.600 --> 00:06:09.030
We're still not
at John Jay's house?

172
00:06:09.120 --> 00:06:10.510
As I wassaying.

173
00:06:10.600 --> 00:06:12.120
I entered the residence
hoping my peers

174
00:06:12.170 --> 00:06:13.560
would focus more on my ideas

175
00:06:13.730 --> 00:06:16.210
than my garments.

176
00:06:16.350 --> 00:06:18.520
That hope was quickly dashed.

177
00:06:20.220 --> 00:06:21.920
What the hell is
wrong with you. Isaac?

178
00:06:22.000 --> 00:06:24.050
I can see the whole
naked bib of your shirt.

179
00:06:24.180 --> 00:06:25.220
It's disgusting.

180
00:06:25.350 --> 00:06:26.350
It wasn't my fault.

181
00:06:26.440 --> 00:06:27.970
There was a mix-up
at the shoppe.

182
00:06:28.050 --> 00:06:30.400
and then it's like. trying
to find a last-minute ruffle

183
00:06:30.580 --> 00:06:31.800
in Manhattan in March...

184
00:06:31.930 --> 00:06:33.370
I mean. while I'm at it.

185
00:06:33.450 --> 00:06:36.580
why don't I just look
for the Northwest Passage?

186
00:06:37.760 --> 00:06:39.150
You are my protégé. Isaac.

187
00:06:39.240 --> 00:06:40.560
When I invited you
to this dinner.

188
00:06:40.590 --> 00:06:42.500
I was sticking my
neck out for you.

189
00:06:42.680 --> 00:06:45.110
and you didn't have the decency
to decorate yours for me?

190
00:06:45.200 --> 00:06:46.030
Look who's here.

191
00:06:46.160 --> 00:06:47.200
Thomas Jefferson.

192
00:06:47.380 --> 00:06:49.810
Ben Franklin. Sam Adams.

193
00:06:49.940 --> 00:06:52.340
I will not have you
embarrass me in my own house.

194
00:06:52.470 --> 00:06:53.730
I don't know what to say.

195
00:06:53.820 --> 00:06:56.040
If you want me to go.
I'll-I'll go.

196
00:06:58.300 --> 00:06:59.480
I-I think I have a spare.

197
00:06:59.610 --> 00:07:00.300
It's not quite
the current style.

198
00:07:00.430 --> 00:07:02.220
but it-it'll suffice.

199
00:07:02.390 --> 00:07:03.310
Come with me.

200
00:07:03.390 --> 00:07:05.440
Yes.

201
00:07:05.610 --> 00:07:07.090
Oh. that's nice of him.

202
00:07:07.270 --> 00:07:08.660
So. everything worked out.

203
00:07:08.750 --> 00:07:10.360
Yes. Samantha.
I'm telling you this story

204
00:07:10.490 --> 00:07:11.690
because everything worked out.

205
00:07:11.840 --> 00:07:13.750
- Geez.
- Let's just say

206
00:07:13.840 --> 00:07:15.580
that this particular ruffle

207
00:07:15.710 --> 00:07:18.630
turned out to be worse
than no ruffle at all.

208
00:07:19.670 --> 00:07:21.760
My God. Higgintoot.
what are you wearing?

209
00:07:21.890 --> 00:07:22.890
It's a loaner.

210
00:07:23.060 --> 00:07:24.630
I know it's not the...

211
00:07:24.760 --> 00:07:26.680
delicate. finely pleated ruffle

212
00:07:26.850 --> 00:07:28.810
that's currently all the rage.

213
00:07:28.940 --> 00:07:31.290
It looks as though you're
being attacked by a swan.

214
00:07:31.460 --> 00:07:32.900
It's enormous.

215
00:07:33.030 --> 00:07:34.876
It's a wonder
you're not toppling over.

216
00:07:34.900 --> 00:07:36.406
I mean. you're
more top-heavy

217
00:07:36.430 --> 00:07:37.990
than Catherine the Great.

218
00:07:39.560 --> 00:07:40.690
You seen paintings of her?

219
00:07:40.820 --> 00:07:42.260
Oh!
Oh. It's nuts.

220
00:07:42.430 --> 00:07:43.820
Are you kidding?

221
00:07:43.910 --> 00:07:45.610
I can't
get enough of them.

222
00:07:45.740 --> 00:07:48.960
You know me... I love looking
at a nice set of plump...

223
00:07:49.090 --> 00:07:49.960
duckies.

224
00:07:50.090 --> 00:07:52.350
But what I love even more is

225
00:07:52.480 --> 00:07:54.310
the fine tailoring at
Henry's Haberdashery.

226
00:07:54.490 --> 00:07:57.100
Which is why I had
reserved my ruffle there.

227
00:07:57.230 --> 00:07:58.930
I'm talking very normal-sized...

228
00:07:59.060 --> 00:08:00.450
modest. even...

229
00:08:00.580 --> 00:08:02.630
with a fine.
handsewn center pleat.

230
00:08:05.060 --> 00:08:06.930
Oh. Sort of like Hamilton's.

231
00:08:07.110 --> 00:08:09.240
Alexander.
you made it!

232
00:08:09.410 --> 00:08:10.680
Happy to be here.

233
00:08:11.770 --> 00:08:12.770
There he was.

234
00:08:12.810 --> 00:08:14.160
Alexander Hamilton.

235
00:08:14.330 --> 00:08:17.030
And he was wearing my ruffle.

236
00:08:18.770 --> 00:08:20.250
Did you just gasp
at your own reveal?

237
00:08:20.430 --> 00:08:21.640
I did.

238
00:08:23.210 --> 00:08:25.959
I am so confused. How did you
even know it was your ruffle?

239
00:08:26.053 --> 00:08:28.052
Are you serious? I ran into him
at the haberdashery

240
00:08:28.079 --> 00:08:29.959
just when my ruffle
was supposed to be ready.

241
00:08:29.990 --> 00:08:32.340
And then he shows up
wearing one that's identical

242
00:08:32.520 --> 00:08:33.780
to the one I reserved?

243
00:08:33.950 --> 00:08:36.170
He must have given them my name

244
00:08:36.310 --> 00:08:38.310
because he wanted
the trendy ruffle.

245
00:08:38.390 --> 00:08:42.440
I could not just let
this injustice stand.

246
00:08:42.530 --> 00:08:44.880
I mean. Angelica is
definitely the prettiest.

247
00:08:44.970 --> 00:08:47.100
Yeah. Sure.
You know. But Eliza just...

248
00:08:47.270 --> 00:08:48.880
She just seems so gettable.

249
00:08:49.010 --> 00:08:50.320
Mm. man. a
Schuyler sister.

250
00:08:50.490 --> 00:08:52.760
I wonder if I
- could get one.
- I mean.

251
00:08:52.890 --> 00:08:54.020
perhaps Peggy.

252
00:08:56.370 --> 00:08:57.590
Right?

253
00:09:02.510 --> 00:09:04.860
Good evening. Alexander.

254
00:09:04.940 --> 00:09:06.420
Lovely ruffle.

255
00:09:06.600 --> 00:09:08.136
You must have reserved it
quite some time ago.

256
00:09:08.160 --> 00:09:10.340
what. considering how slammed
all the haberdasheries

257
00:09:10.510 --> 00:09:11.950
have been this ruffle season.

258
00:09:12.040 --> 00:09:14.560
Yes. yes. Ruffle season
certainly has been

259
00:09:14.690 --> 00:09:15.740
hot. hot. hot.

260
00:09:15.820 --> 00:09:17.220
Which is why

261
00:09:17.350 --> 00:09:20.130
I reserved mine with
Mr. Henry two weeks ago.

262
00:09:20.260 --> 00:09:21.350
Oh. You know.

263
00:09:21.480 --> 00:09:23.270
funny thing...
I also reserved mine

264
00:09:23.350 --> 00:09:25.350
with Mr. Henry two weeks ago.

265
00:09:25.530 --> 00:09:26.960
But when I showed up today.

266
00:09:27.090 --> 00:09:28.660
mine had gone missing.

267
00:09:28.790 --> 00:09:31.140
And yet here you are.

268
00:09:31.230 --> 00:09:32.880
wearing an identical piece.

269
00:09:33.010 --> 00:09:34.360
How interesting.

270
00:09:34.540 --> 00:09:36.670
And another interesting fact...

271
00:09:36.840 --> 00:09:40.190
I had my ruffle monogrammed
on the inside of the collar.

272
00:09:40.930 --> 00:09:42.720
Monogrammed. you say?

273
00:09:42.810 --> 00:09:44.240
Indeed.

274
00:09:44.370 --> 00:09:46.810
Gentlemen.
Let's convene the meeting.

275
00:09:46.980 --> 00:09:49.380
I'd like to polish off
the rest of this draft tonight.

276
00:09:49.510 --> 00:09:51.550
so we can get on
with the signing.

277
00:09:51.680 --> 00:09:52.510
The signing.

278
00:09:52.640 --> 00:09:54.510
Hot stack of johnnycakes.

279
00:09:54.640 --> 00:09:57.340
you really were gonna sign
the Declaration of Independence!

280
00:09:57.430 --> 00:10:00.260
It really looked like it.
So what happened?

281
00:10:00.390 --> 00:10:03.220
So. let's talk about
these unalienable rights.
Mm.

282
00:10:03.350 --> 00:10:07.310
So far. I have life and liberty.

283
00:10:07.480 --> 00:10:09.180
But it feels like
there should be a third.

284
00:10:09.350 --> 00:10:10.180
Mm.

285
00:10:10.310 --> 00:10:11.970
What about beer?

286
00:10:12.100 --> 00:10:14.580
Thank you. Sam. Uh. I'm not
gonna write that down.

287
00:10:14.710 --> 00:10:16.470
but that doesn't mean
that it was a bad idea.

288
00:10:16.540 --> 00:10:17.620
Either way. we need

289
00:10:17.750 --> 00:10:18.996
to make it clear
that these rights

290
00:10:19.020 --> 00:10:20.150
were given to us by God...

291
00:10:20.280 --> 00:10:22.540
I think Hamilton took it.

292
00:10:24.540 --> 00:10:26.020
Took what?

293
00:10:26.150 --> 00:10:27.460
My ruffle.

294
00:10:27.590 --> 00:10:29.420
The one I reserved at Henry's.

295
00:10:29.550 --> 00:10:31.720
Who cares?
We're founding a nation.

296
00:10:31.860 --> 00:10:33.510
Just drop it. man.

297
00:10:34.470 --> 00:10:35.340
Now.

298
00:10:35.420 --> 00:10:37.340
the people should have the right

299
00:10:37.430 --> 00:10:38.730
to alter

300
00:10:38.860 --> 00:10:41.430
or even abolish government.
if abused.

301
00:10:41.600 --> 00:10:42.740
But at the same time...

302
00:10:42.870 --> 00:10:45.560
Do you think he bribed him?

303
00:10:45.700 --> 00:10:46.740
Bribed who?

304
00:10:46.870 --> 00:10:48.610
The haberdasher.

305
00:10:48.700 --> 00:10:50.790
Are you not listening?
I am trying to listen.

306
00:10:50.920 --> 00:10:53.700
To Jefferson. Just
leave me alone.
Okay.

307
00:10:53.880 --> 00:10:55.946
And we can no longer
tolerate the forced boarding

308
00:10:55.970 --> 00:10:57.920
of foreign mercenaries
in our homes.

309
00:10:58.010 --> 00:10:59.540
Mm-hmm.

310
00:10:59.670 --> 00:11:01.320
It's just. the timing
is so suspicious.

311
00:11:01.450 --> 00:11:03.060
what it is that they...

312
00:11:03.230 --> 00:11:04.630
John.

313
00:11:04.710 --> 00:11:05.710
John.

314
00:11:05.800 --> 00:11:08.070
John Jay...
Higgintoot!

315
00:11:08.200 --> 00:11:09.890
Yeah...
Did you have
something

316
00:11:10.020 --> 00:11:11.300
that you would like
to contribute

317
00:11:11.370 --> 00:11:12.590
to this particular concept?

318
00:11:12.770 --> 00:11:15.030
I. um...

319
00:11:15.200 --> 00:11:16.990
Yeah. I like it. It's good.

320
00:11:17.120 --> 00:11:18.510
And what was it?

321
00:11:19.690 --> 00:11:20.770
I don't know.

322
00:11:22.080 --> 00:11:24.430
Man. you are blowing this.

323
00:11:27.610 --> 00:11:29.390
There are many benefits.

324
00:11:29.570 --> 00:11:33.050
Sometimes I even get to come
to Earth as a living human.

325
00:11:33.130 --> 00:11:34.400
otherwise known as a demon.

326
00:11:34.530 --> 00:11:35.530
While here.

327
00:11:35.660 --> 00:11:37.270
I'm wining. I'm dining.

328
00:11:37.400 --> 00:11:39.750
I am tricking innocents
into selling me their souls.

329
00:11:39.880 --> 00:11:41.050
It is a blast.

330
00:11:41.140 --> 00:11:44.410
And all on
the underworld's dime.

331
00:11:44.580 --> 00:11:46.970
Honestly. it sounds a lot like
my time at Lehman Brothers.

332
00:11:47.100 --> 00:11:48.166
Any of you could be having fun

333
00:11:48.190 --> 00:11:49.320
like me.

334
00:11:49.500 --> 00:11:51.060
All you have to do
is accept my deal.

335
00:11:51.200 --> 00:11:52.850
A simple handshake will do.

336
00:11:52.980 --> 00:11:54.046
Oh. get that hand away from me.

337
00:11:54.070 --> 00:11:55.070
I ain't taking the deal.

338
00:11:55.160 --> 00:11:57.290
Nor should any of us.

339
00:11:57.460 --> 00:11:59.250
Aside from possibly Thor.

340
00:11:59.330 --> 00:12:00.810
What Thor do?

341
00:12:00.940 --> 00:12:02.160
"What Thor do?"

342
00:12:02.340 --> 00:12:03.876
Didn't you kill.
like. thousands of people?

343
00:12:03.900 --> 00:12:06.170
Yes. but only
to pillage the land

344
00:12:06.300 --> 00:12:07.860
for resources and treasure.

345
00:12:07.990 --> 00:12:10.340
Also. must remember.
most of those were Dane.

346
00:12:10.480 --> 00:12:13.300
so Thor think Thor in clear.

347
00:12:13.480 --> 00:12:14.910
Danes are people. too. Thor.

348
00:12:15.090 --> 00:12:16.310
She's not wrong.

349
00:12:16.440 --> 00:12:18.000
my wolf-urine-soaked friend.

350
00:12:18.140 --> 00:12:19.400
You see. in the eyes of hell.

351
00:12:19.570 --> 00:12:21.530
all nationalities
are seen as equal.

352
00:12:23.180 --> 00:12:24.970
I was surprised. too.

353
00:12:25.140 --> 00:12:28.800
But Thor kill many. many Dane.

354
00:12:28.930 --> 00:12:33.800
And also. eat best friend Oskar.
who was squirrel.

355
00:12:33.890 --> 00:12:36.630
See. the equating of those
two things also isn't great.

356
00:12:36.760 --> 00:12:38.110
Think I have
a live one.

357
00:12:38.200 --> 00:12:39.640
What do you say
we make it official?

358
00:12:39.810 --> 00:12:41.550
Oh. that's enough. Elias.

359
00:12:41.680 --> 00:12:43.136
He doesn't want your deal.
None of us do.

360
00:12:43.160 --> 00:12:45.770
So open up a hole and go back
down from where you came.

361
00:12:45.860 --> 00:12:47.950
Well. you all have
another hour on the clock.

362
00:12:48.030 --> 00:12:49.860
If you change your
minds. I will be around

363
00:12:50.040 --> 00:12:53.560
looking for Livings
to walk through and make horny.

364
00:12:54.610 --> 00:12:56.040
Okay. that guy sucks.

365
00:12:56.220 --> 00:12:58.700
but you got to admit.
that ghost power rocks.

366
00:13:00.050 --> 00:13:02.010
Men? I do believe

367
00:13:02.090 --> 00:13:05.050
that we have done something
important here tonight.

368
00:13:05.180 --> 00:13:07.530
And now it is time to sign.

369
00:13:07.660 --> 00:13:09.530
Huzzah!

370
00:13:10.840 --> 00:13:12.620
There I was.

371
00:13:12.760 --> 00:13:14.670
mere inches away...

372
00:13:14.840 --> 00:13:17.190
From signing the Declaration
of Independence?

373
00:13:17.280 --> 00:13:20.810
From the monogrammed collar
of my ruffle.

374
00:13:22.290 --> 00:13:24.200
I know it's you.

375
00:13:24.330 --> 00:13:26.550
You stole my ruffle.

376
00:13:26.640 --> 00:13:28.210
I don't know what
you're talking about.

377
00:13:28.290 --> 00:13:29.746
and we're kind of in
the middle of something.

378
00:13:29.770 --> 00:13:31.160
Well. let me see the collar.

379
00:13:31.340 --> 00:13:32.860
What?
No. let me see it.

380
00:13:33.040 --> 00:13:34.170
No. No.
Let me see it.

381
00:13:34.340 --> 00:13:35.600
What is wrong with you?

382
00:13:35.780 --> 00:13:36.870
Isaac. what are you doing?

383
00:13:39.130 --> 00:13:39.780
Put it out!

384
00:13:39.910 --> 00:13:41.090
My God. man!

385
00:13:41.220 --> 00:13:42.520
Uh. I can save it.

386
00:13:42.610 --> 00:13:43.920
No. no...

387
00:13:44.000 --> 00:13:45.400
No!

388
00:13:45.530 --> 00:13:46.660
My beer.

389
00:13:46.830 --> 00:13:48.700
Phew. That was close.

390
00:13:48.830 --> 00:13:51.490
You destroyed it. Higgintoot.

391
00:13:51.620 --> 00:13:53.710
No. no. I-I mean...

392
00:13:53.840 --> 00:13:55.890
Honestly. we were gonna
have to do it over anyway.

393
00:13:56.020 --> 00:13:58.540
'cause all those S's
look like F's.

394
00:14:00.720 --> 00:14:01.980
Oh. my goodness.

395
00:14:02.110 --> 00:14:04.460
You destroyed
the Declaration of Independence?

396
00:14:04.590 --> 00:14:06.850
Just the first draft. but yes.

397
00:14:08.640 --> 00:14:11.368
So you destroyed the first draft
of the Declaration

398
00:14:11.393 --> 00:14:13.003
and squandered your
own shot at history.

399
00:14:13.053 --> 00:14:14.533
At least there's
a silver lining.

400
00:14:16.430 --> 00:14:19.260
Damn it. Pete. don't start
one unless you got it.

401
00:14:19.440 --> 00:14:21.790
I spilled a glass of wine on
Paul Simon's white couch once.

402
00:14:21.960 --> 00:14:23.640
Took Garfunkel a week
to get the stain out.

403
00:14:23.700 --> 00:14:25.440
Oh. man.

404
00:14:25.620 --> 00:14:27.920
Timothée Chalamet's eating
at Connor's restaurant.

405
00:14:28.010 --> 00:14:30.620
I'm sorry. is he even
listening to my story?

406
00:14:30.750 --> 00:14:32.490
Jay. Isaac wants you
to focus up.

407
00:14:32.670 --> 00:14:36.110
I am focusing. but there's a
lot of downtime between updates.

408
00:14:36.240 --> 00:14:37.760
Where was I? Ah. yes.

409
00:14:37.850 --> 00:14:41.290
Fine. not my finest moment.
but all is not lost.

410
00:14:41.460 --> 00:14:43.656
Jefferson. you seem to have
a pretty good handle on things.

411
00:14:43.680 --> 00:14:45.460
How about you take
another run at the draft?

412
00:14:45.640 --> 00:14:47.810
And then we'll all meet
back here. same time next week

413
00:14:47.940 --> 00:14:50.340
for some beers
and sign-aroonies?

414
00:14:50.420 --> 00:14:54.170
I'm sorry. Higgintoot.
but. uh. you're out.

415
00:14:54.300 --> 00:14:55.730
Me?

416
00:14:55.820 --> 00:14:57.740
If anyone should be out.
surely it's Hamilton.

417
00:14:59.000 --> 00:15:00.090
And why is that?

418
00:15:00.170 --> 00:15:03.570
Because he stole my ruffle.

419
00:15:03.700 --> 00:15:05.440
He's spiraling.
He's totally lost it.

420
00:15:05.610 --> 00:15:07.350
Who invited this guy?

421
00:15:07.440 --> 00:15:09.440
I think he just showed up.

422
00:15:09.570 --> 00:15:11.320
Higgintoot...

423
00:15:12.400 --> 00:15:13.710
it is time to leave.

424
00:15:13.840 --> 00:15:16.800
Fine. I'll leave.

425
00:15:16.890 --> 00:15:19.060
but not without regret.

426
00:15:19.190 --> 00:15:21.410
Nothing would have
made me happier

427
00:15:21.500 --> 00:15:23.890
than to contribute
to this great cause.

428
00:15:24.020 --> 00:15:27.240
But alas. Alexander interfered

429
00:15:27.370 --> 00:15:30.160
with my pursuit of happiness.

430
00:15:33.160 --> 00:15:35.380
Because of the whole
ruffle kerfuffle.

431
00:15:35.470 --> 00:15:37.040
Get out!

432
00:15:37.210 --> 00:15:39.780
Adding insult to injury.

433
00:15:39.870 --> 00:15:43.350
Hamilton volunteered
to lead me to the door.

434
00:15:43.520 --> 00:15:47.870
saving for my exit
one final twist of the knife.

435
00:15:48.000 --> 00:15:52.010
I'm sorry
things didn't work out.

436
00:15:52.140 --> 00:15:55.530
Oh. and. um. Higgintoot?

437
00:15:55.660 --> 00:15:57.060
You were right.

438
00:15:57.190 --> 00:15:59.280
I stole your ruffle.

439
00:16:02.500 --> 00:16:05.280
Hamilton admitted
to stealing Isaac's ruffle.

440
00:16:05.370 --> 00:16:08.720
So Isaac was right.
Hamilton did do it.

441
00:16:08.810 --> 00:16:10.370
Yes. Jay.

442
00:16:10.500 --> 00:16:13.070
But the truth is.
that's not what matters.

443
00:16:13.160 --> 00:16:16.900
The only thing that matters
is that my blind obsession

444
00:16:17.030 --> 00:16:18.640
with proving that

445
00:16:18.770 --> 00:16:22.260
caused me to miss out
on being a part of history.

446
00:16:22.390 --> 00:16:27.040
Jay. this restaurant
is your shot at making history.

447
00:16:27.170 --> 00:16:30.570
Don't let it pass you by.

448
00:16:30.700 --> 00:16:32.326
Isaac's saying
he should've just let it go

449
00:16:32.350 --> 00:16:33.750
and not worried about it.

450
00:16:33.880 --> 00:16:36.050
because he missed his chance
to make his mark.

451
00:16:36.230 --> 00:16:38.580
Isaac's right.

452
00:16:38.710 --> 00:16:41.060
I need to stop sitting around
and complaining

453
00:16:41.190 --> 00:16:42.670
and start doing everything
in my power

454
00:16:42.710 --> 00:16:45.100
to make my restaurant a success.

455
00:16:45.230 --> 00:16:47.280
This might be
way too late

456
00:16:47.370 --> 00:16:50.330
to be asking.
but what is a ruffle?

457
00:16:50.410 --> 00:16:53.110
Honestly. I got to say.
I knew hell was bad.

458
00:16:53.200 --> 00:16:55.550
but it sounds really bad.
Totally.

459
00:16:55.640 --> 00:16:57.640
Except for the constant playing
of Chumbawamba.

460
00:16:57.770 --> 00:16:59.900
which is objectively awesome.

461
00:17:00.080 --> 00:17:01.560
So. do we have a deal?

462
00:17:01.690 --> 00:17:02.730
Thor. no.

463
00:17:02.860 --> 00:17:04.056
You don't want to do this.
Big Guy.

464
00:17:05.520 --> 00:17:07.740
But Thor may be
going to hell anyways.

465
00:17:07.870 --> 00:17:12.480
Why not take deal and make
things little more comfortable?

466
00:17:12.610 --> 00:17:14.506
Trust me. he does not want
to start on the ground floor.

467
00:17:14.530 --> 00:17:16.740
I mean. for one. that
floor is made of snakes.

468
00:17:16.880 --> 00:17:20.230
Thor. think about it.
you've been here a long time.

469
00:17:20.360 --> 00:17:21.660
If you were gonna go down on us.

470
00:17:21.750 --> 00:17:24.010
don't you think it would have
already happened?

471
00:17:24.140 --> 00:17:25.710
What you mean?
I'm saying yes.

472
00:17:25.840 --> 00:17:29.540
you've done some bad stuff.
but you've been making efforts

473
00:17:29.670 --> 00:17:31.280
to improve yourself.
Mm.

474
00:17:31.410 --> 00:17:33.200
And maybe the universe
is taking note.

475
00:17:33.370 --> 00:17:35.720
You remember two years ago
when Bela's boyfriend Eric

476
00:17:35.810 --> 00:17:36.980
was electrocuted

477
00:17:37.160 --> 00:17:39.770
and you saved his life
using your ghost power?

478
00:17:39.900 --> 00:17:42.340
Yeah. Thor. that's one life
back in the plus column.

479
00:17:42.420 --> 00:17:43.966
You do that a couple
more thousand times.

480
00:17:43.990 --> 00:17:45.380
you're pretty much even.

481
00:17:45.470 --> 00:17:47.910
Don't listen to them.
We're hell buddies.

482
00:17:48.080 --> 00:17:51.260
And you remember all those years
as a ghost when you watched

483
00:17:51.390 --> 00:17:53.350
over me as a young girl?

484
00:17:53.480 --> 00:17:55.610
Comforting me
in my times of need.

485
00:17:55.700 --> 00:17:57.420
Maybe we've all been given
a chance to learn

486
00:17:57.480 --> 00:18:00.220
from our mistakes
and become better people.

487
00:18:00.400 --> 00:18:02.310
And no one's done that
more than you.

488
00:18:04.920 --> 00:18:07.670
Sorry. Elias...

489
00:18:09.670 --> 00:18:12.710
but Thor decide
to take Thor's chances.

490
00:18:12.800 --> 00:18:15.280
Fine. but know this:
I will not rest

491
00:18:15.410 --> 00:18:17.720
until I reap one soul
from this house.

492
00:18:17.850 --> 00:18:19.240
Believe me when I say.

493
00:18:19.370 --> 00:18:21.770
you have not seen
the last of me.

494
00:18:25.030 --> 00:18:26.030
Morons.

495
00:18:26.070 --> 00:18:27.640
That is the cue.

496
00:18:27.820 --> 00:18:29.380
That is always the cue.

497
00:18:29.470 --> 00:18:30.990
You have not seen the last...

498
00:18:31.080 --> 00:18:33.260
♪ I get knocked down.
but I get up again... ♪
Ooh.

499
00:18:33.430 --> 00:18:34.210
♪ I get knocked down ♪

500
00:18:34.390 --> 00:18:36.220
♪ But I get up again ♪

501
00:18:36.300 --> 00:18:37.870
♪ You're never gonna
keep me down... ♪

502
00:18:38.000 --> 00:18:40.220
God. it's such a good song.

503
00:18:40.310 --> 00:18:41.610
Isaac.

504
00:18:41.740 --> 00:18:43.270
Something you said
got me thinking.

505
00:18:43.440 --> 00:18:45.620
Did you ever actually
read the final version

506
00:18:45.750 --> 00:18:47.140
of the Declaration
of Independence?

507
00:18:47.270 --> 00:18:49.490
As a matter of fact. no.

508
00:18:49.660 --> 00:18:51.400
Once I blew my chance
to be a part of it.

509
00:18:51.540 --> 00:18:53.190
I couldn't bear
to look at the thing.

510
00:18:53.280 --> 00:18:55.450
Right. 'cause there's a phrase
you said in the story.

511
00:18:55.630 --> 00:18:57.280
"Pursuit of happiness."

512
00:18:57.410 --> 00:18:59.566
Yes. it was something I said
in the heat of the moment.

513
00:18:59.590 --> 00:19:01.760
They can't all be winners.

514
00:19:01.850 --> 00:19:03.290
Well. they used it.

515
00:19:03.420 --> 00:19:04.656
Right at the beginning
of the Declaration.

516
00:19:04.680 --> 00:19:06.680
What? Really?

517
00:19:06.810 --> 00:19:08.770
"Certain unalienable rights.

518
00:19:08.860 --> 00:19:11.770
Life. liberty
and the pursuit of happiness..."

519
00:19:11.860 --> 00:19:13.510
They used my words.

520
00:19:13.640 --> 00:19:15.120
So I guess you did

521
00:19:15.300 --> 00:19:17.560
make your mark on history.
in kind of a big way.

522
00:19:17.690 --> 00:19:19.780
I guess I did.
What about "ruffle kerfuffle"?

523
00:19:19.870 --> 00:19:21.040
Did that make it in?

524
00:19:21.130 --> 00:19:22.000
Uh. I'm pretty sure no.

525
00:19:22.130 --> 00:19:23.440
Okay. Well. still.

526
00:19:23.570 --> 00:19:25.310
Isaac: one. Hamilton: zero.

527
00:19:25.440 --> 00:19:27.480
Well. I mean.
he's on the ten-dollar bill.

528
00:19:27.610 --> 00:19:29.570
Yeah. okay. then it's a draw.

529
00:19:29.700 --> 00:19:32.580
Which is the best Hamilton's
ever done in a duel. am I right?

530
00:19:32.710 --> 00:19:34.100
Yeah. h-he died.

531
00:19:34.270 --> 00:19:36.320
Yes. he did. The wimp.

532
00:19:36.450 --> 00:19:39.020
Whereas I am immortal.

533
00:19:39.150 --> 00:19:41.190
My words live on.

534
00:19:42.190 --> 00:19:43.330
I have to tell the others.

535
00:19:43.460 --> 00:19:46.370
Everyone? I'm famous!

536
00:19:46.500 --> 00:19:47.980
Whereas Hamilton

537
00:19:48.110 --> 00:19:49.640
bled out in a field
in New Jersey.

538
00:19:49.720 --> 00:19:52.030
I bet he was really
ruffled about that.

539
00:19:52.120 --> 00:19:54.860
Can't endorse the pettiness.
but love the pun.

540
00:19:56.440 --> 00:19:58.220
If I'm being honest.
part of me isn't sure

541
00:19:58.350 --> 00:19:59.790
about hiring a publicist.

542
00:19:59.960 --> 00:20:02.210
I know I'm a good chef.
Shouldn't that be enough?

543
00:20:02.300 --> 00:20:04.690
Everyone needs
a little help sometimes.

544
00:20:04.820 --> 00:20:07.910
I don't know. it kind of feels
like I'm selling my soul.

545
00:20:08.080 --> 00:20:10.650
I completely understand.

546
00:20:12.570 --> 00:20:13.740
You know what?

547
00:20:13.870 --> 00:20:15.440
I'm gonna have
to think about it.

548
00:20:15.530 --> 00:20:16.740
Take as much time as you need.

549
00:20:16.920 --> 00:20:18.490
And when you've made
your decision.

550
00:20:18.620 --> 00:20:21.010
you know how to get
in touch with me.

551
00:20:27.540 --> 00:20:30.450
♪ I get knocked down. but I get
up again. you're never... ♪
